The Mean and Median

  • In order understand large datasets, we need to summarize, but how we summarize matters!
  • The mean and median are two ways of describing the “typical” data-point
    • Question: Which colored line depicts the mean? Which measure better reflects the number of nitrogen atoms of a “typical” compound in this dataset?

Other Summary Statistics

  • Thinking only in terms of the “typical” data-point can be dangerous, often we are interested in values that aren’t typical

  • Suppose the vehicles in the cartoon drive 2 feet from the center-line, we might consider reporting the proportion of the drunk’s positions outside of (-2, 2)
  • Alternatively, if we don’t know how far the vehicles are from the center-line, we could report certain percentiles of the drunk’s positions
    • For example, if the 90% percentile is 1.1, this indicates 90% of the drunk’s positions are less than 1.1 feet above the center-line
    • You can find percentiles in R using the quantile function
x <- seq(1:100)
quantile(x, probs = .1)
##  10% 
## 10.9
quantile(x, probs = .9)
##  90% 
## 90.1

Image from “The Flaw of Averages”: Link

Variability

  • Summaries of the “typical” data-point suffer from another flaw, they don’t express the variation in the data
    • The means of \(x = \{2,5,7,10\}\) and \(y = \{5,6,6,7\}\) are both 6, but \(x\) and \(y\) are clearly very different
  • Means are used reported accompanied by a standard deviation or a standard error
    • Question: What’s the difference between these? (this should be review)

Standard Deviation vs. Standard Error

  • Standard Deviation describes the variability of the data - how spread out the data-points are around their mean
  • Standard Error describes the uncertainty of an estimate - we might see our data as a sample representing some population, so we use sample mean is an estimate of a population characteristic
    • We may choose to use the standard error to derive a confidence interval
    • If the sampling distribution is approximately normal, we are 95% confident the population characteristic is within 1.96 standard errors of the sample estimate
Mean SD SE 95% CI
Solubility -2.74 2.05 0.06 (-2.8,-2.68)
Number of Oxygen Atoms 1.53 1.68 0.05 (1.48,1.58)
  • Question: Based upon this table, does the solubility of a compound appear related to how many oxygen atoms it contains?

Pairwise Associations

  • With univariate summaries (like the mean), we lose any information about how the variables are related
    • This is a big deal, as most applications center around relating two or more variables
  • One way of evaluating association between two variables (pairwise associations) is to use visualization
    • Question: Based upon the graph below, is there an association between the number of oxygen atoms and a compound’s solubility?

Pairwise Associations - Correlation

  • The plot tells us a lot about the association, compounds with more oxygen atoms tend to have higher solubility scores
    • But exactly how strong is this relationship?
  • The correlation coefficient is one way of quantifying the association between two numeric variables
    • Like before, if we consider our data a sample we might report the correlation coefficient accompanied by an uncertainty measure
    • The cor function can be used to find correlations, the cor.test can be used to find accompanying confidence intervals
cor(x = data$NumOxygen, y = data$Solubility)
## [1] 0.1158384
cor.test(x = data$NumOxygen, y = data$Solubility)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  data$NumOxygen and data$Solubility
## t = 4.1479, df = 1265, p-value = 3.579e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.06115601 0.16982747
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.1158384
  • Question: How would you describe the relationship between these variables? Are they strongly associated? Do you think they could be unrelated?

Conclusion and Remarks on Hypothesis Testing

  • The first step in any data analysis is to learn about your variables
    • Summarization, in the form of summary statistics and/or visuals, is essential in this process
  • Recognizing that most data comes with uncertainty is another critical aspect of data science/statistics
    • You consider using confidence intervals to quantify how a sample statistic might generalize to a broader population
  • In this class we won’t place much empthasis on hypothesis testing, but you should be aware of it. For certain projects, hypothesis testing is a nature choice and a very useful tool
